<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Malaconothridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">MALACONOTHRIDAE</taxonomicName>
Berlese, 1916
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
Berlese (1896b, pp. 26-27) classified 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Nothridae" genus="Nothrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="monodactylus">Nothrus monodactylus Michael</taxonomicName>
(1888, p. 528, pl. 45 figs. 10-14) as 
<taxonomicName authority="Berlese, 1885" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1885" class="Arachnida" family="Lohmanniidae" genus="Angelia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Oribatida" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="monodactyla">Angelia monodactyla</taxonomicName>
with the 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Nothridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Nothridae</taxonomicName>
1). Afterwards (Berlese, 1913a) the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Malaconothridae" genus="Malaconothrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Malaconothrus</taxonomicName>
Berlese, 1904 (to which 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Nothridae" genus="Nothrus" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="monodactylus">monodactylus</taxonomicName>
belongs) was classified in a tribe (
<taxonomicName pageId="74" pageNumber="75" rank="tribe" tribe="Michaeliini">Michaeliini</taxonomicName>
) of this family. Finally, Berlese (1916a, pp. 175, 176) created a separate family 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Malaconothridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Malaconothridae</taxonomicName>
, consisting of the tribes 
<taxonomicName pageId="74" pageNumber="75" rank="tribe" tribe="Malaconothrini">Malaconothrini</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName pageId="74" pageNumber="75" rank="tribe" tribe="Lohmannini">Lohmannini</taxonomicName>
. At present the genera 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Malaconothridae" genus="Malaconothrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Malaconothrus</taxonomicName>
Berlese (1904) and 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Malaconothridae" genus="Trimalaconothrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Trimalaconothrus</taxonomicName>
Berlese (1916) are the only representatives of the family; 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Trhypochthoniidae" genus="Mucronothrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Mucronothrus</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="TrÃ¤gardh" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">Traegardh</normalizedToken>
(1931) is according to Hammer (1958, p. 25) related to 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Trhypochthoniidae" genus="Trhypochthoniellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Trhypochthoniellus</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
1) Berlese (1896b) records 
<taxonomicName authority="Berlese, 1885" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1885" class="Arachnida" family="Lohmanniidae" genus="Angelia" genus.bestMatchDistance="117" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Oribatida" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="monodactyla">A. monodactyla</taxonomicName>
from England only; possibly he had not seen the species.
</paragraph>
